<h1>The Epic Tradition</h1>
<p>There was literature before Gilgamesh, but we don't have any. It's the beginning for us.</p>
<ul>
	<li>History, religion, fictional. Society was loose about history. Gilgamesh was a person, he was a king. We've separated superheroes from religious icons, but they didn't back then. The Illyad was the bible of Ancient Greece. Political as well - make me Aeneid for propoganda. Using our fiction to create the values we want. History and fiction is written by the winners - they decide what was or is important.</li>
	<li>Oral tradition - most epics were not designed to be read, they were designed to be spoken. Pneumonics - meant to be recited. They had to be easy to remember. Human beings used to be able to remember novels. Illyad circled for 500 years until someone wrote it down. </li>
	<li>Standard Elements
		<ul>
			<li>@@in media res@@ - starts in the middle. Flash forward/flash back. Harder to follow chronology, but makes audience members pay more attention. </li>
			<li>@@innumeratio@@ - list of combatants. second chapter - list everyone who was there. Theory: people who preformed the stories put their name into the list so it got really big. We still do this by showing each character and what they can do.</li>
			<li>@@anticipatio@@ tells you how it will end - spoiler, but intentional. The story becomes more about how it will happen, and not what happens. </li>
			<li>@@avocatio@@ invocation of the muse. "God wrote it." The idea that it was written by a divine being. </li>
		</ul>
		Some transfer to the Superhero, but not all. 
	</li>
</ul>

<h1>The Epic of Gilgamesh</h1>
<p>2000 BC. Samarion/Babylonian. Was on clay tablets.</p>
<ul>
	<li>Book 1: Surpassing All Kings - about Gilgamesh being awesome even though his people hate him. Focuses bromance with Enkidu. Reflects Sumerian values. How awesome life it is. Flaunts mortality. </li>
	<li>Book 2: He Who Saw the Deep - tale of Gilgamesh's grief for Enkidu. Considered Babylonian. How awful life is. About mortality. </li>
</ul>
<p>Conversion Text. Tell the story of Gilgamesh and then alter things for my new empire. Takes all original ideas, and alters them to their ideas. </p>
<p>Subtheme: one of them wants to do this. they do it. "I'm scared." "Be strong." </p>
<p>Friendship, grief, mortal fear. </p>
