<ul>What does Superman do? Two types of fantasy: 
	<li>@@Power Fantasy@@ you wish you were more powerful. You can live your fantasies of being powerful. Superman was providing murder. 
<ul>
	<li>Superman Complex. A desire to see other people suffer for righteous reasons while you yourself are untouched. This is something all of us do. We enjoy that grimm, horrible spectacle. Rubbernecking - slowing down to look at the car crash. </li>
	<li>Geek demographic. The geek is no longer an underclass. We no longer look down on people who are smart. Our Clark Kent can be geeky without us resenting him. Deadpool is a massive geek - sounds like he's a fanboy all the time. </li>
	<li>Mad Scientist defeated. Characters that stand in for concepts that scare us. Almost always villains. We were really scared of science. It was automating our jobs. We don't like change. Superman pummels defeats punches scientists. Power of the natural defeating the technological. </li>
	<li>Flight. When they fly above the city, visual metaphor to escape the urban environment. Crowds of people make you feel not special. You want that power to be above it all.</li>
	<li>Importance - messiah complex. Ordinary shlum who discovers they're actually really powerful. Neo from the Matrix, Harry Potter. Everybody cares what he does because he's going to change the world. </li>
</ul>
	
	</li>
	<li>@@Protector Fantasy@@ Like Santa Claus, religion. Ideal being that if you do good things, you will be taken care of. If you do bad things, you will be punished.
<ul>
	<li>Atomic bomb appeasor. Don't want real brutality as they've already seen it. </li>
	<li>Protects the innocent. He didn't do that before WW2. If you are a good person, Superman won't let anything bad happen to you. </li>
	<li>Preserves divide between good and evil. At the time, society needed that. Evil will be punished, good will be rewarded. </li>
	<li>Uses power justly - Superman will not abuse his power. He has the power, but it's okay he has the power. The power was the atomic bomb - everyone feared, had to hope they wouldn't use it. </li>
	<li>Reaffirms the value of human life. Superman will not kill. Even if you commit genocide, Superman wants to bring you to court. </li>
	<li>Preserves the American way. Good if you're American. </li>
	<li>Personification of God. Santa Claus == Jesus Christ.</li>
</ul>
	</li>
	<li></li>
</ul>
<p>Before WW2, it was all power fantasy. After WW2, balance between power and protector fantasy. You can't have Superman without a little bit of power fantasy. Power fantasy coming back as WW2 is moving further away. The further we are from global conflict, the more power fantasy. They contradict each other. Hard to have a powerful and non-threatening being. Satisfy both at the same time. Double think - have paradox in your brain, but not recognize it. </p>

<p>How do you think Superman stories can satisfy both at the same time? </p>
<ul>
	<li>empower the villain - Superman has a worthy opponent who he can beat. Lex Luthor in a suit</li>
	<li>reluctant hero - gets to do awesome stuff, but doesn't want to. </li>
	<li>weakness - kryptonite. important narrative for you to feel afraid for Superman. </li>
	<li>extended frailty - superman would lay down his life. What would hurt him is if a bystander gets killed, or Lois Lane. Worried about the people he loves. Not physical threat to Superman, but threat to his loved ones. </li>
	<li>burden of responsibility - if you had the power to save everybody, you would want to save everybody. Can't enjoy life because he can always be saving someone. </li>
	<li>dual-identity - Clark isn't Superman. Clark is a lonely, failure socially, sexually frustrated. He's committed to living a normal life. Sexual frustration gets talked about a lot. The most powerful warriors gets lots of lots of sex, but Superman does not. </li>
	<li>Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs - Superman doesn't need food. Superman doesn't need safety. After that is social acceptance. The one thing Superman needs is social acceptance, which he's not getting. Lois Lane is in love with Superman. Clark Kent is in love with Lois Lane. The thing he desires the most, he does not have it. </li>
	<li></li>
</ul>

	
